1
0:00:25,000 --> 0:00:27,000
I'm Michael Shermer, director of the Skeptics Society,

2
0:00:27.556,000 --> 0:00:28,000
publisher of "Skeptic" magazine.

3
0:00:29.112,000 --> 0:00:3,000
We investigate claims of the paranormal,

4
0:00:31.049,000 --> 0:00:34,000
pseudo-science, fringe groups and cults, and claims of all kinds between,

5
0:00:34.755,000 --> 0:00:36,000
science and pseudo-science and non-science and junk science,

6
0:00:37.673,000 --> 0:00:4,000
voodoo science, pathological science, bad science, non-science,

7
0:00:41,000 --> 0:00:42,000
and plain old non-sense.

8
0:00:42.911,000 --> 0:00:43,000
And unless you've been on Mars recently,

9
0:00:44.852,000 --> 0:00:46,000
you know there's a lot of that out there.

10
0:00:46.894,000 --> 0:00:49,000
Some people call us debunkers, which is kind of a negative term.

11
0:00:49.94,000 --> 0:00:51,000
But let's face it, there's a lot of bunk.

12
0:00:52.072,000 --> 0:00:55,000
We are like the bunko squads of the police departments out there --

13
0:00:55.549,000 --> 0:00:58,000
well, we're sort of like the Ralph Naders of bad ideas,

14
0:00:59,000 --> 0:01:,000
(Laughter)

15
0:01:00.254,000 --> 0:01:02,000
trying to replace bad ideas with good ideas.

16
0:01:03,000 --> 0:01:04,000
I'll show you an example of a bad idea.

17
0:01:04.887,000 --> 0:01:05,000
I brought this with me,

18
0:01:06.069,000 --> 0:01:09,000
this was given to us by NBC Dateline to test.

19
0:01:1,000 --> 0:01:13,000
It's produced by the Quadro Corporation of West Virginia.

20
0:01:13.31,000 --> 0:01:15,000
It's called the Quadro 2000 Dowser Rod.

21
0:01:16.244,000 --> 0:01:17,000
(Laughter)

22
0:01:17.714,000 --> 0:01:22,000
This was being sold to high-school administrators for $900 apiece.

23
0:01:23,000 --> 0:01:27,000
It's a piece of plastic with a Radio Shack antenna attached to it.

24
0:01:27.351,000 --> 0:01:28,000
You could dowse for all sorts of things,

25
0:01:29.341,000 --> 0:01:32,000
but this particular one was built to dowse for marijuana

26
0:01:32.758,000 --> 0:01:33,000
in students' lockers.

27
0:01:34,000 --> 0:01:36,000
(Laughter)

28
0:01:36.484,000 --> 0:01:39,000
So the way it works is you go down the hallway,

29
0:01:40.053,000 --> 0:01:42,000
and you see if it tilts toward a particular locker,

30
0:01:43.076,000 --> 0:01:44,000
and then you open the locker.

31
0:01:44.544,000 --> 0:01:45,000
So it looks something like this.

32
0:01:46.145,000 --> 0:01:47,000
I'll show you.

33
0:01:48.809,000 --> 0:01:49,000
(Laughter)

34
0:01:5,000 --> 0:01:53,000
Well, it has kind of a right-leaning bias.

35
0:01:53.415,000 --> 0:01:55,000
Well, this is science, so we'll do a controlled experiment.

36
0:01:56.244,000 --> 0:01:57,000
It'll go this way for sure.

37
0:01:57.85,000 --> 0:02:,000
(Laughter)

38
0:02:01.808,000 --> 0:02:03,000
Sir, do you want to empty your pockets, please, sir?

39
0:02:04.358,000 --> 0:02:05,000
(Laughter)

40
0:02:06.22,000 --> 0:02:09,000
So the question was, can it actually find marijuana in students' lockers?

41
0:02:09.701,000 --> 0:02:11,000
And the answer is, if you open enough of them, yes.

42
0:02:12.323,000 --> 0:02:13,000
(Laughter)

43
0:02:13.37,000 --> 0:02:14,000
(Applause)

44
0:02:15,000 --> 0:02:18,000
But in science, we have to keep track of the misses, not just the hits.

45
0:02:18.405,000 --> 0:02:21,000
And that's probably the key lesson to my short talk here:

46
0:02:21.695,000 --> 0:02:24,000
This is how psychics work, astrologers, tarot card readers and so on.

47
0:02:25.453,000 --> 0:02:27,000
People remember the hits and forget the misses.

48
0:02:27.696,000 --> 0:02:28,000
In science, we keep the whole database,

49
0:02:29.615,000 --> 0:02:31,000
and look to see if the number of hits somehow stands out

50
0:02:32.3,000 --> 0:02:34,000
from the total number you'd expect by chance.

51
0:02:34.537,000 --> 0:02:35,000
In this case, we tested it.

52
0:02:35.855,000 --> 0:02:36,000
We had two opaque boxes:

53
0:02:37.371,000 --> 0:02:4,000
one with government-approved THC marijuana, and one with nothing.

54
0:02:41.029,000 --> 0:02:42,000
And it got it 50 percent of the time --

55
0:02:42.934,000 --> 0:02:43,000
(Laughter)

56
0:02:44.051,000 --> 0:02:46,000
which is exactly what you'd expect with a coin-flip model.

57
0:02:47,000 --> 0:02:5,000
So that's just a fun little example here of the sorts of things we do.

58
